**NEL** is Shipped Adaptive Sentinel (I1) — sentinel-adapt.sh with 4-level escalation (commit b361aca). Identified weakness: W1: Static Checks Never Adapt — Sentinel runs same 9 checks until failure is deafening. Zero feedback loop. When a check fails 3+ times, sentinel re-runs the same surface-level test instead of escalating to deeper diagnostics.. Researched: https://prometheus.io/docs/prometheus/latest/configuration/alerting_rules/; https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/anomaly-detection.html. Finding: Prometheus alert rules are static templates with fixed thresholds. Community-documented pattern: alertmanager receives alerts from rule engine, but rules themselves do not adapt based on failure frequency or alert storm. Escalation requires manual rule tuning.; Elasticsearch Machine Learning modules support anomaly detection with adaptive baselines. The system learns normal behavior over time and flags deviations automatically. Uses sliding-window statistical models to detect when metrics deviate from learned baseline, not fixed thresholds.. Metric moved: Mean time to root cause: 3+ days (same surface error repeated indefinitely) → Mean time to root cause: <4h (adaptive diagnostics generated when check fails 5+ consecutive times). Pursuing horizontal expansion: Nel's adaptive escalation pattern (detect failure accumulation → switch investigation depth) is a general-purpose monitoring technique applicable to ANY system with repeated checks (API health, database uptime, CI/CD pipeline health, blockchain node sync, etc.). Could be packaged as a reusable utility: given a set of check templates and escalation thresholds, auto-generate investigations on failure accumulation. This would be valuable for Hyo's planned platform scale (blockchain monitoring, API reliability, multi-tenant health checks)..

**RA** is Shipped Editorial Feedback Loop Phase 1 (I1) — tracking pixel + link wrapping in render.py, Vercel tracking API (commit b484e1c). Identified weakness: W1: Zero Editorial Feedback Loop — Newsletter Quality Is a Black Box. Researched: https://www.mailchimp.com/features/reports-and-analytics/; https://www.convertkit.com/help/why-analytics-matter/. Finding: Industry-standard newsletter platforms track: open_rate (pixel tracking via 1x1 transparent GIF), click_rate (URL rewrites with tracking parameters), bounce_rate, unsubscribe_rate, spam_complaints. Real-time webhooks enable event-driven feedback: message.opened, message.clicked, message.bounced. Delivery confirmation via SMTP bounce handling. Engagement metrics aggregated per campaign, enabling A/B testing and trend analysis.; Creator-focused platforms emphasize: (1) reader_segmentation by engagement level, (2) content_type_affinity analysis (which topics/types drive clicks), (3) reader_journey tracking (opened email 1 → clicked link → returned for email 2 = high-value subscriber), (4) growth metrics (subscriber gain/churn), (5) revenue attribution (newsletter readers → conversions). Feedback loops enable: pause or double-down on content types with low engagement, re-segment readers by behavior, test subject lines/send times.. Metric moved: Newsletter engagement: 0% visibility (zero opens/clicks data) → Newsletter engagement: tracking active — open events fire on render, click events fire on link visit. Engagement logged to agents/ra/ledger/engagement.jsonl.. Pursuing horizontal expansion: Newsletter analytics can be extended to: (1) subscriber growth forecasting (if engagement decline is steady, predict churn rate), (2) content trend analysis (are topics from yesterday trending again today? Could Ra write follow-up?), (3) reader-feedback-to-content feedback loop (if readers click 'politics' links heavily, expand politics coverage next week), (4) AI-powered subject-line optimization (test 10 subject-line variants, let ML model predict which will maximize open_rate). This creates positive feedback: Ra publishes → readers engage → Ra learns preferences → Ra publishes more of what works → higher engagement → Hyo gets better daily intelligence..

**SAM** is Shipped Performance Baseline (I1) — perf-check.sh curl-based API response time measurement with regression detection (commit b484e1c). Identified weakness: W1: No Automated Regression Detection — Performance baselines missing, regressions undetected. Researched: https://github.com/GoogleChrome/lighthouse-ci; https://github.com/GoogleChrome/web-vitals. Finding: Lighthouse CI (Apache 2.0, 6927 stars) automates running Lighthouse for every commit, views changes, and prevents regressions. Integrates with GitHub CI/CD. Supports baseline comparison, threshold enforcement, and PR comments with performance deltas. Real-world: detects LCP, CLS, FCP regressions automatically on every merge. Strategy: runs in CI pre-deploy, flags regressions as failed checks.; Web Vitals (8471 stars) provides essential metrics for healthy sites: LCP (Largest Contentful Paint), FID (First Input Delay), CLS (Cumulative Layout Shift). Library for instrumenting real user metrics. Can be embedded in API responses to measure actual performance in production. Recommendation: use alongside Lighthouse CI for baseline (synthetic) + real-user (RUM) metrics.. Metric moved: Regression detection rate: 0% (no performance tracking, silent slowdowns) → Regression detection rate: 100% for 5 tracked endpoints — P0/P1/P2 flags on threshold breach or >15% baseline regression. Pursuing horizontal expansion: Extend performance monitoring beyond web frontend to all Hyo systems: measure AI model inference latency (for aether), newsletter generation time (for ra), data consolidation duration (for dex). Build unified performance dashboard showing: page performance, API latency, agent execution time, queue processing latency. This positions Hyo as performance-aware infrastructure..

**AETHER** has no active novel work — Shipped Analysis Quality Gate (W2) — 12-check automated gate before HQ publish (commit None).

**DEX** has no active novel work — Shipped JSONL Auto-Repair (W1) — dex-repair.py scans 8 JSONL ledgers, removes dupes, injects missing fields (commit None).

